# Introduction

Engineers have always been expected to prepare designs that can withstand extreme conditions. In the case of collection system infrastructure, rainfall is a critical consideration since stormwater inflow can quickly overwhelm a system's capacity and cause flooding. Consequently, there is a need to quantify the various intensities of rainfall that might occur over the life of a design. This need is typically fulfilled by national rainfall atlases published by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Agency (NOAA). NOAA's Atlas 14 is divided into eleven volumes that each cover a different region of the United States. To develop statistics for each region, NOAA collected and analyzed time series of annual maximum precipitation observed at multiple gages within each region and used statistical extreme value analysis (EVA) to estimate the probability of rainfall intensities at various durations. The analysis is very thorough, and the resulting product serves as the standard for a wide variety of design and planning activities and regulations across the US. However, the Atlas is lacking in several areas:

1.  Atlas datasets have not been updated since their initial publication. Atlas 14 has no data after 2000 for the 17 states analyzed in its first two volumes, and lacks coverage for five northwestern states.

2.  Atlas 14 provides statistics for only a select set of durations and average recurrence intervals (ARI), limiting a user\'s ability to easily quantify ARIs outside of or between those values; and

3.  While the Atlas provides the information necessary to evaluate the significance of historical rainstorms, it does not provide software tools for quickly and easily applying its statistics to time series data.

To address these limitations, an engineer needs to acquire hourly or higher frequency rainfall data and conduct their own EVA, which is not straightforward. Public rainfall data sources often require extensive post-processing to isolate relevant records and screen out erroneous data. Furthermore, some data sources (such as NOAA's Integrated Surface Dataset) are not simple to access, requiring knowledge of NOAA file systems to find data rather than through concise web forms. Conducting an EVA is a multi-step procedure that requires using programming techniques to extract statistically independent storm totals at various durations and fitting those data to a continuous extreme value distribution. From the fitted distributions, intensity-duration-frequency (IDF) curves can be developed and ARIs can be calculated for historical storm events. Finally, upper and lower confidence intervals around each IDF curve may be calculated using a Monte Carlo simulation procedure. CDM Smith's NetSTORM software has grown over its 30-year history to automate accomplishing all these tasks.

NetSTORM provides several functions for easily downloading recent data from NOAA and United States Geological Survey (USGS) web services. Users can quickly get the latest rainfall data from those public sources and reformat and disaggregate them for input to models or frequency analyses. NetSTORM can also rapidly conduct an EVA, binning rainfall data into events, quantifying magnitudes and durations, and developing ARIs for each event. The results of the analysis are summarized in a comprehensive and portable web page that can easily be shared with others or exported into a spreadsheet for further analysis (examples at <http://www.dynsystem.com/netstorm/IDFStats.htm>). NetSTORM's output not only develops IDF curves directly from time series data, but also provides a means to better contextualize the latest rainfall events with the local period of record.

NetSTORM was used to rapidly contextualize the impacts from Tropical Storms Fred (8/19/2021), Henri (8/22/2021), and Ida (9/1/2021) for Hartford\'s Metropolitan District (MDC) and the Town of West Hartford. Both Fred and Ida caused significant flooding in the Hartford area (shown in **Figure 3**). The algorithms used by NetSTORM are presented in the methods section below. The results of the analyses are presented in the results and discussion section.

# NETSTORMS RAINFALL ANALYSIS METHODS

## Fundamentals of Extreme Value Analysis: Extreme Value Extraction and Model Selection

Statistics are most often applied to estimate central metrics for a *"population"* by examining the distribution of a *"sample"*; for example, finding the average height of all people by measuring the heights of a few thousand. Extreme value analysis is a branch of statistics that estimates the true maximum or minimum values of a population by examining the extreme values in multiple samples. Although the most extreme values of a population may never have been measured any sample, EVA provides a framework for quantifying their magnitude by fitting observed extremes to a continuous statistical distribution. NetSTORM applies the principles of extreme value analysis to rainfall time series data to contextualize storm events with historical data and establish IDF curves. An EVA starts with extraction of an extreme value series from a sample dataset, of which there are two types: block maxima (BM) and peaks over threshold (POT).

Block maxima extreme values are extracted by first selected a block size (typically one year in rainfall analysis), partitioning the sample time series into equally sized consecutive blocks, and extracting a single maximum value for each block. A continuous statistical distribution is then fit to the resulting BM time series, which can be used to model extreme value probabilities.

POT extreme values are extracted by first choosing a threshold value and selecting all higher values. The resulting POT series (also known as partial duration series or PDS) is then declustered to ensure that all the values have enough time between them to attain statistical independence. For example, it would be inappropriate to select two 24-hour blocks in a 36-hour storm since they represent a single event and would include overlapping data. A continuous statistical distribution is fit to the declustered POT time series, which can be used to model extreme value probabilities.

BM and POT methods have different strengths and weakness. A BM series is well-defined and simple to extract from a rainfall time series; calculating a rolling 24-hour window sum and extracting the largest window from each year in the time series is all that is required for extracting a 24-hour storm annual maximum series. However, because multiple extreme events may occur in a single year, the BM method excludes data points that can be valuable for an EVA. The difficulty in any extreme value analysis is the limited amount of data for statistical model fitting. Because extreme data are by definition scarce, extreme ARI estimates typically exhibit large variance. The POT method maximizes the number of extreme events used in an EVA to better characterize extreme event probability and reduce the variance in fitted model results. However, developing a partial duration series with the POT method is more complex because an appropriate threshold must be selected. Too low a threshold includes more common events, violating the basis of the extreme value model and leading to bias. Too high a threshold yields too few data points with which to fit the model, leading to high variance and eliminating the benefit of the POT method over the BM method.

Because the BM and POT take different approaches of extreme value series extraction, their resulting series are distributed differently. **Figure 4** shows the distribution of all 24-hour storms measured at Bradley International Airport (Windsor Locks, Connecticut) from 1955 through 2021 compared to those of the 24-hour annual maximum series and the partial duration series with a threshold depth of 2.5 inches.

However, once ARIs are developed, they are converted to partial duration series-based ARIs using an empirical formula (Langbein, 1949). NetSTORM derives ARIs directly from partial duration series. However, rather than using threshold values to isolate series, NetSTORM selects the largest *n*-storms out of the *n*-years of data. NetSTORM's approach simplifies threshold selection for the POT method, which is the major challenge in the procedure.

There are several ways to fit the GEV or GPD to rainfall data including the method of moments (Coles, 2001), maximum likelihood (Coles, 2001), generalized maximum likelihood (Martins, 2000), and L-moments (Hosking, 1990). NetSTORM utilizes the L-moments method to fit distributions to data, matching the Atlas 14 approach.

## Fitting a Model to Data: An L-moments Approach

The L-moments method works well for fitting the GEV to rainfall data because it is less impacted by outliers than the previously mentioned methods. L-moments are expectations of linear combinations of order statistics and are analogous to conventional moments such as mean, variance, skew, and kurtosis. However, because L-moments are linear functions of the data, they suffer less from sample variability (Hosking, 1990), which can be higher in the smaller sample sizes present in rainfall data. **Figure 7** presents the GEV and GPD fit to the 24-hour BM and POT series presented in **Figure 4**. The probability density plots illustrate how different shapes of the GEV and GPD cater to the BM and POT distributions respectively, demonstrating the basis for the Fisher--Tippett--Gnedenko and Pickands--Balkema--De Haan theorems.

## Calculating Average Recurrence Intervals and Developing IDF Curves

Average recurrence intervals, also referred to as return periods, are often misinterpreted. It is incorrect to say that a 100-year storm is a storm that occurs once every 100 years, as this statement does not properly convey the nature of the statistical probability on which the ARI is based. It is more correct to say that a 100-year storm has an exceedance probability in any given year of 1% and would increase when considering longer time periods according to **Equation 1**. For example, over 50 years, a 100-year storm would have an exceedance probability of about 40% ($1  (1  0.01)^{50}$).

ARIs are calculated from exceedance probabilities using **Equation 2** (Coles, 2001). Given the CDF functions shown in **Figure 7** and the relationship between exceedance probability and ARI in **Equation 2**, plots of storm depth vs ARI can be created to yield IDF curves, shown in **Figure 8**.

___

$$
\begin{align*}
P &= 1 - (1-p)^n  \tag{1} \\
\\
{ where} & \\
P &= \text{Total exceedance propbability} \\
p &= \text{Annual exceedance probability} \\
n &= \text{Number of years}
\end{align*}
$$



$$
\begin{align*}
R       & = \frac{1}{p\mathrm{/}\lambda}\ \tag{2}\
\\
{ where} \\
R       & = \text{Return period as a multiple of the desired return period size (typically 1 year)} \\
p       & = \text{Exceedance probability determined from the fitted distributions cumulative distribution function (CDF)}\\
\lambda & = \text{Rate of extreme events from the BM or POT time series} \\
\\
        & \;\;\;\; \lambda = \frac{\textit{return period size}}{\textit{block size}}\;\;\;\text{for BM time series (=1/1 for an annual maximum series)}\\
        \\
        & \;\;\;\; \lambda = \frac{n}{\frac{t}{\textit{return period size}}}\;\;\;\text{for POT time series}\\   
        \\
        & \;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\; {where} \\
        & \;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;  n = \text{Number of extreme events in the time series} \\
        & \;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;  \textit{return period size} = \text{Return period unit size (typically 1 year)} \\
        & \;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;  t = \text{Total duration of the POT time series as a multiple of }\textit{return period size}
\end{align*}
$$

Because of the nature of **Equation 2,** extreme value distributions fit to an annual maximum series or a low frequency partial duration series cannot be used to approximate low ARIs. The lowest ARI that can be estimated from a GEV fit to an annual maximum series is 1 year, while the lowest from a GPD fit to a partial duration time series depends on the selected threshold and time series duration but should generally not be much lower than 1-year. However sub-annual ARIs are often of interest for combined sewer system overflow studies for which the 3- or 6-month storms are typical benchmarks. NetSTORM identifies sub-annual ARIs using an empirical plotting position approach. Probabilities are derived directly from the full storm depth time series using the rank of each storm along with a plotting position parameter (see **Equation 3**).

___

$$
\begin{align*}
R &= \frac{n+1-2b}{r-b}\tag{3} \\
\\
{ where} & \\
R &= \text{ARI (years)} \\
n &= \text{Number of years}\\
r &= \text{Rank of storm depth in the time series (ranked in descending order)}\\
b &= \text{Empirical plotting position parameter. Suggested value of 0.4 (Cunnane, 1978)}\\
\end{align*}
$$

___

To develop IDF curves, extreme time series (BM or POT) are first extracted at various durations (e.g., 1-, 2-, 6-, 12-, 24-, 48-hour). A GEV or GPD is then fit to each time series depending on the EVA approach, and the CDF functions shown in **Figure 7** are used in conjunction with **Equation 2** to calculate the storm depth for ARIs ranging from 1 year to 1000 years. **Equation 3** is then used to calculate storm ranks for ARIs less than 1 year and the storm depth is extracted from the time series based on that rank. The storm depth for each ARI is plotted against storm duration to yield final IDF curves.

## IDF Confidence Intervals

As mentioned in the previous section, extreme value data are scarce by definition. Consequently, when fitting a distribution to such scarce data, the resulting model should consider the inherent variability that comes with small sample sizes. To better understand the accuracy of probabilistic storm depths derived from GEV and GPD models, confidence limits are developed that provide the upper and lower limits of how large a certain storm might be with a given duration and ARI. In other words, although a fitted model might indicate that a 10-year 24-hour storm is 4 inches, that estimate is based only on the sample data used to fit the model, which is limited to the gage's period of record. It is not possible to calculate the "true" value of a 10-year 24-hour storm, because the gage would need to include the entire "population" of rainfall data at the site, which would require data over the entire period of our current climate. However, confidence intervals can be used to identify the likely range within which that true value lies.

NetSTORM uses a Monte Carlo approach to develop confidence intervals. After extracting annual maximum or partial duration time series and developing IDF curves, the fitted distribution is randomly resampled with replacement one thousand times, creating one thousand alternative time series that are slightly different from the original. IDF curves are developed from each of these alternative time series, producing slightly different models. The 5^th^ and 95^th^ percentile curves are extracted from those models to represent the lower and upper confidence boundaries respectively. **Figure 9** presents the same GEV curve shown in **Figure 8**, but also includes the upper and lower confidence boundaries from a 1,000 generation Monte Carlo simulation. The faint blue lines in the figure are the fit GEV curves from each alternative dataset created. The distance between the ARI confidence boundaries widens as storm depth increases because there are fewer large storms, which increases data variance in that range and decreases confidence in the ARI estimate.

**Table 3** shows the ARI of each depth shown in **Table 2**, estimated by both NetSTORM's analysis of BDL data and from interpolation of Atlas 14. Fred has the highest ARI at both gages, measuring approximately 25 years at BDL and approximately 191 or 267 years at NBPR based on NetSTORM and Atlas 14 respectively. Ida received significantly more news coverage than Fred before it struck the area because it was generally a larger and more intense storm with seriously impacts in other areas of the country (NOAA, 2021). However, Fred was more extreme at shorter durations in Hartford, which better contextualizes the flooding shown in **Figure 3**.

# CONCLUSIONS

Hartford-area rainfall data were rapidly evaluated using NetSTORM in the aftermath of three intense storms that occurred in the span of two weeks. The program identified historical, meteorologically independent storm events in the data, then quantified their rainfall intensities at various durations. The resulting data were used in an extreme value analysis that follows similar methods to those used in NOAA's Atlas 14, quantifying average recurrence intervals and building IDF curves directly from the largest available local dataset currently spanning 1955 through the present.

Although both Tropical Storms Fred and Ida exhibited similar daily total rainfall, the extreme value analysis indicated that Fred was the much rarer event having a maximum ARI of about 250 years based on the NOAA IDF curves and about 200 years based on NetSTORM's. These results better contextualize the significant flooded condition in the Hartford area following Fred, for which there was less public forewarning since it was generally a smaller storm than Ida in most other regions of the country.

Performing frequency analysis of rainfall can be challenging, requiring one to navigate the complex landscape of meteorological data access, partition data into statistically independent events, then perform statistical extreme value analysis. NetSTORM has evolved over its 30-year history to streamline this process. The software produces concise, portable web page output that can inform other analyses or serve as standalone reports. While non-stationarity of rainfall now and in the future means that precipitation frequency estimates are subject to change, the statistics published in Atlas 14 and elsewhere are generally valid for understanding historic rainfall, and likely only warrant modest adjustment for assessing extreme rainfall over the next few decades.
